3/13/24, 10:18 PM - Naqabi: تلاوت کلام پاک کرتے وقت کیا نیت و ارادہ کرنا چاھیے ؟

 بہت سے مسلمان قرآن مجید کی تلاوت کرتے ھوئے محض اجر و ثواب کی نیت کرتے ہیں۔
جبکہ قرآن پاک کی تلاوت کرتے وقت مزید کئی بڑی نیتیں بھی کی جا سکتی ہیں جس سے اکثر لوگ ناواقف ہیں 

 حالانکہ قرآن پاک کی تلاوت کے وقت درج ذیل نیتیں کرنے سے قرآن پاک کے بے شمار انعامات و ثمرات سے بھی مستفید ھو سکتے ہیں 
 
جیسا کہ نبی کریم صلی اللہ علیہ وسلم نے فرمایا:

* إنَّمَا الْأَعْمَالُ بِالنِّيَّاتِ، وَإِنَّمَا لِكُلِّ امْرِئٍ مَا نَوَى*

 * "اعمال کا دارومدار نیتوں ہی پر ہے۔ اور ہر شخص کے لیے وہی کچھ ہےجس کی اس نے نیت کی”* - ( مفہوم حدیث)

 قرآن پاک کی تلاوت کے وقت درج ذیل نیتیں بھی کر لی جائیں تو یقینا اس تلاوت پر ہم بے بہا انعامات حاصل کر سکتے ہیں :-  
جیسا کہ ۔۔۔۔

 1- میں علم اور اس پر عمل کی نیت سے قرآن مجید پڑھتا ھوں ۔ 

 2- میں اللہ تعالی سے ہدایت کے ارادے و نیت سے قرآن مجید پڑھتا ھوں ۔ 

 3- میں اللہ تعالی کو یاد کرنے کی نیت سے قرآن مجید پڑھتا ھوں ۔ 

 4 - میں اپنی ظاہری و باطنی ( جسمانی و روحانی ) بیماریوں سے پاک ہونے کے ارادے و نیت سے قرآن مجید پڑھتا ھوں ۔ 

 5- میں اس نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں کہ اللہ تعالی مجھے اندھیروں سے نکال کر روشنی اور نور عطا فرما دیں ۔ 

 6- میں اس نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں کہ اللہ تعالی میرے دل کی سختی کو دور کر دیں اور میرے دل کو نرم فرما دیں ۔

 7- میں اس نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں کہ اللہ تعالی میرے سینے کے تفکرات کو ختم فرما دیں ۔ 

 8- میں اس نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں کہ میں غافل لوگوں میں نہ لکھا جاوں بلکہ یاد رکھنے والوں میں شمار کیا جاوں ۔ 

 9- میں اس نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں کہ اللہ تعالی کی ذات و صفات پر میرے یقین اور ایمان میں ترقی و اضافہ ھو ۔ 

 10-  میں اس نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں کہ اللہ تعالٰی کے حکم کی تعمیل کرنے والا بن جاوں ۔ 

 11- میں قرآن مجید کو ثواب کے لئے پڑھتا ہوں ، تاکہ مجھے اسکے ہر حرف کے بدلے 10 نیکیاں ملیں اور اللہ تعالی اپنے فضل سے مزید بڑھا کر عطا فرما دیں ۔ 

 12-  میں اس نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں کہ  قیامت کے دن مجھے قرآن کریم کی شفاعت حاصل ھو جائے ۔ 

 13- میں رسول اللہﷺ کے حکم کی تعمیل کی نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں ۔ 

 14- میں اس نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں کہ اللہ تعالی قرآن مجید کے سبب مجھے بلند مرتبہ والوں میں شمار فرما دے۔ 

 15-  میں اس نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں کہ قرآن مجید کی وجہ سے اللہ تعالی مجھے جنت میں داخل فرما دے اور مجھے اور میرے والدین کو تعظیم کا تاج پہنا دے ، اور میرے والدین کو کرامت کا لباس پہنا کر جنت میں داخل فرمادے ۔ 

 16- میں اس نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں کہ اسکا پڑھنا مجھے اللہ تعالی کے قریب کر دے ۔ 

 17-  میں اس نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں کہ میں اللہ تعالی کے خاص بندوں میں شامل ہوجاؤں۔

 18-  میں اس نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں کہ معزز فرشتوں کے ساتھ ھو جاوں اور اللہ تعالی مجھے قرآن کے ماھر میں شمار فرمادے ۔ 

 19- میں جھنم کی آگ اور اللہ تعالی کے عذاب سے بچنے کی نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں ۔ 

 20- میں اس نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں کہ مجھے اللہ تعالی کی معیت ( تعلق ) نصیب ھو جاے۔ 

 21-  میں اس نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں کہ میں دنیا و آخرت کی ذلت ورسوائی سے بچ جاوں  ۔ 

 22-  میں اس نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں کہ یہ قرآن میرے حق خلاف دلیل نہ بنے بلکہ میرے حق میں دلیل بنے ۔ 

 23-  میں اس نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں کہ اللہ تعالی مجھے اس پر ثابت قدمی عطا فرما دے ۔ 

 24-  میں اس نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں کہ مجھے سکینہ ( اطمینان ) ملے اور رحمت مجھ پر نازل ہو اور اللہ تعالی کی بارگاہ میں میرا تزکرہ ھو ۔ 

 25- میں اللہ تعالی سے خیر اور فضل کے حصول کے ارادے سے قرآن مجید پڑھتا ہوں۔

 26-  میں اس نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں کہ مجھے پاک ھوا ( خوشبو ) نصیب ہو ۔ 

 27-  میں اس نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں کہ میں اس دنیا میں گمراہ نہ ہوں اور نہ ہی آخرت میں دکھی ہوں۔

 28-  میں اس نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں کہ اس کی برکت سے مجھ سے رنج و غم  اور پریشانیوں کو دور کر دیا جائے ۔ 

 29-  میں اس نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں کہ قبر میں مجھے قرآن سے مجھے ( انسیت ) ھو ، اس دنیا میں میری رہنمائی کرے ، اور مجھے جنت میں لے جائے۔

 30-  میں اس نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں کہ اللہ تعالی مجھے حلم دے اور مجھ کو رسول صلی اللہ علیہ وسلم والے اخلاق سے مزین فرما دے۔ 

 31-  میں اس نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں کہ حق پر قائم رھوں اور جھوٹ اور باطل سے محفوظ رھوں ۔ 

 32-  میں اس نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں کہ مجاھدہ نفس حاصل کر کے نفس و شیطان اور اسکے مکر و فریب سے محفوظ رھوں ۔ 

 33-  میں اس نیت سے قرآن پڑھتا ھوں کہ اللہ تعالی قیامت کے دن میرے اور کافروں کے درمیان پردہ حائل فرما دے۔

 تو آئیے قرآن مجید والے لوگوں میں سے بنیں !!
 
یقینا یہ اللہ تعالی کے ساتھ نفع بخش تجارت ہے ، جس پر اللہ تعالی اپنی رحمت اور کبھی نہ ختم ہونے والا فضل و احسان  عطا فرما تے ہیں ۔ 
یا اللہ یہ تمام انعامات ہم سب کو عطا فرما 
( آمین یا رب العالمین )

5/8/24, 9:20 PM - Naqabi: 🔷 چار بیویاں 🔷

ایک شخص کی چار بیویاں تھیں،
چوتھی بیوی سے وہ بہت محبت کرتا تھا اور اس کو بنانے سنوارنے میں ہر وقت لگا رہتا تھا۔

تیسری بیوی سے بھی وہ محبت کرتا تھا کیونکہ وہ بہت خوبصورت تھی جو اسے دیکھتا گرویدہ ہو جاتا اسی لئے اس کو یہ خوف لگا رہتا تھا کہ یہ کسی اور کی نہ ہو جائے۔ اس لئے اسے چھپا چھپا کر رکھتا تھا۔

دوسری سے بھی اسے بہت محبت تھی اس لئے کہ وہ اسکی ساری پریشانیوں کا حل اسے بتاتی اور ہمیشہ اس کی مدد کرتی رہتی۔

مگر پہلی!!! پہلی سے وہ محبت نہیں کرتا تھا لیکن وہ اس سے بدستور محبت کرتی تھی۔

------اب ہوا یہ کہ -----
ایک دن وہ شخص اتنا بیمار ہوا کہ مرنے کے قریب ہوگیا، اس نے سوچا میرے پاس چار بیویاں ہیں کسی ایک کو تو مرتے ہوئے ساتھ لے جاؤں۔

اس  نے چوتھی بیوی سے کہا کہ تم میرے ساتھ چلو----  میں نے تم پر اتنی توجہ دی اور اپنا مال بھی تم پر سب سے زیادہ خرچ کیا-

★-- جواب میں اس نے صاف صاف انکار کر دیا۔

تیسری بیوی سے کہا تو اس نے جواب دیا کہ---
★-- دنیا میں ابھی میرے چاہنے والے بہت ہیں میں کسی کی بھی ہو جاؤں گی۔

دوسری بیوی نے کہا کہ---
★-- میں صرف قبر تک تو ساتھ آ جاؤں گی مگر اس سے آگے میں نہیں آسکتی۔

اب یہ بڑا پریشان ہوا اچانک پیچھے سے آواز آئی کہ میں تمہارے ساتھ قبر تک چلوں گی،
★-- اگرچہ تم نے کبھی میری طرف توجہ نہیں کی۔

جب اس نے پیچھے مڑ کر دیکھا تو وہ اس کی پہلی بیوی تھی جو عدم توجہی اور غذا کی کمی کی وجہ سے بالکل کمزور ہوچکی تھی۔
جس کے سبب قبر میں اس کے کسی کام کی نہ تھی۔

اب یہ افسوس کرتا رہا کہ---
میں نے سمجھنے میں غلطی کی
اگر میں اس پر توجہ دیتا تو آج یہ قبر میں میری اچھی رفیق اور ساتھی  ہوتی۔

🌹 وضاحت ۔۔۔
چوتھی بیوی سے مراد --- ہمارے اعضاء ہیں جن کو بنانے سنوارنے میں تو ہم لگے رہتے ہیں 
مگر مرتے ہی یہ ہمارا ساتھ چھوڑ دیتے ہیں۔

تیسری بیوی سے مراد ---
ہمارا مال و منال، دولت و جائیداد وغیرہ ھے کہ ساری زندگی لوگوں سے چھپا کر رکھا 
مگر مرنے کے بعد یہ دوسروں کے  ہو جاتے ہیں۔

دوسری بیوی سے مراد ---
ہمارے اہل و عیال رشتے دار اور دوست احباب ہیں، دنیا میں یہی لوگ ہمارے کام آتے ہیں، ہمارے مسائل حل کرواتے ہیں، ہم ان سے جتنی اور جیسی چاہیں مدد لیتے رہیں  مگر یہ لوگ بھی زیادہ سے زیادہ قبر تک ہمارا ساتھ دے سکتے ہیں۔

پہلی بیوی سے مراد ---
ہمارے اعمال ہیں- جو قبر میں ساتھ جائیں گے۔ لیکن ہم نے ان کی طرف توجہ نہ دے  کر قبر کے حقیقی دوست رفیق اور ساتھی سے محروم ہو جاتے ہیں۔

6/3/24, 2:43 PM - Muhammad Fawwad Ahmed: Considering the various dimensions and criteria of a mental disorder (Deviance, Dysfunction, Discomfort, Maladaptive Behavior, Norm or Value Violation), analyze the following cases to determine if each individual meets the criteria for a psychological disorder.

Provide your reasoning, specifying which criteria are met or not met.

yeh heading hai
6/3/24, 2:43 PM - Muhammad Fawwad Ahmed: yeh case study hai
Case 1

Simon is extremely upset about the death of his brother 2 days ago. He has not been able to sleep or to eat, and he was barely able to take a shower and dress for the funeral. Since he found out about the death, he has spent most of his time crying and talking to relatives about his brother.
6/3/24, 2:44 PM - Muhammad Fawwad Ahmed: Case 2

John has always been a friendly and outgoing person. However, in the past six months, he has developed a habit of washing his hands excessively. He washes his hands about 30 times a day, even when they are not dirty. This habit is starting to interfere with his daily life. John finds it difficult to complete tasks at work on time because he feels the need to wash his hands so frequently. He also feels embarrassed about his behavior and tries to hide it from his colleagues and friends. Despite these challenges, John is still able to maintain his job and social relationships, but he feels very distressed about his inability to control his handwashing.

yeh case 2 hai
6/3/24, 2:44 PM - Muhammad Fawwad Ahmed: 11 minute hain jaldi jawab daina
6/3/24, 2:48 PM - Naqabi: _Analysis:_

- Deviance: No, his behavior is a normal response to a significant loss.
- Dysfunction: Yes, his behavior is impairing his daily functioning (sleep, eating, self-care).
- Discomfort: Yes, he is experiencing significant distress and emotional pain.
- Maladaptive Behavior: No, his behavior is a natural response to grief.
- Norm or Value Violation: No, his behavior is consistent with cultural norms for grieving.

_Conclusion:_ Simon does not meet the criteria for a psychological disorder at this time. His behavior is a normal and adaptive response to a significant loss, and he is allowing himself to process his emotions and grieve. It's important to note that grief can be a long process, and if Simon's symptoms persist or worsen over time, it may be worth re-evaluating his mental health. However, at this point, his behavior is a natural response to a difficult situation.
6/3/24, 2:49 PM - Naqabi: _Analysis:_

- Deviance: Yes, his behavior deviates from societal norms (excessive handwashing).
- Dysfunction: Yes, his behavior interferes with daily functioning (impacts work performance, social relationships).
- Discomfort: Yes, he experiences distress, embarrassment, and feels unable to control his behavior.
- Maladaptive Behavior: Yes, his behavior is harmful (excessive handwashing can lead to skin irritation, social isolation).
- Norm or Value Violation: Yes, his behavior violates cultural norms (excessive handwashing is viewed as unusual).

_Conclusion:_ John meets the criteria for a psychological disorder, likely Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder (OCD). His excessive handwashing is an compulsion that is distressing, dysfunctional, and deviates from societal norms. While he is still able to maintain his job and social relationships, his behavior is causing significant distress and impairment in his daily life. It's important for John to seek professional help to address his OCD symptoms and develop coping strategies to manage his anxiety and behavior.

6/5/24, 12:07 AM - Naqabi: *Case 1:*
A 25-year-old woman, Sarah, believes she is a cat and meows frequently, licks her hands, and avoids water.

*Analysis:*

- Deviance: Yes, her behavior deviates from societal norms.
- Dysfunction: Yes, her behavior interferes with daily functioning.
- Discomfort: No, she doesn't seem to experience distress.
- Maladaptive Behavior: Yes, her behavior is harmful (avoiding water can lead to hygiene issues).
- Norm or Value Violation: Yes, her behavior violates cultural norms.

*Conclusion:* Sarah meets criteria for a psychological disorder, likely a Delusional Disorder or Schizophrenia.
6/5/24, 12:07 AM - Naqabi: *Case 2:*
A 30-year-old man, John, experiences excessive worry about his health, constantly checks his body for signs of illness, and avoids social events due to fear of embarrassment.

*Analysis:*

- Deviance: Yes, his behavior deviates from societal norms.
- Dysfunction: Yes, his behavior interferes with daily functioning and relationships.
- Discomfort: Yes, he experiences anxiety and distress.
- Maladaptive Behavior: Yes, his behavior is harmful (excessive worry, social withdrawal).
- Norm or Value Violation: Yes, his behavior violates cultural norms.

*Conclusion:* John meets criteria for a psychological disorder, likely Generalized Anxiety Disorder or Social Anxiety Disorder.
6/5/24, 12:07 AM - Naqabi: - Case 3: Emily, a 28-year-old marketing executive, experiences excessive worry about her job performance, finances, and relationships, and has difficulty sleeping, concentrating, and controlling her worry.

 *Analysis:* 

- Deviance: Yes, her excessive worry and anxiety deviate from societal norms.
- Dysfunction: Yes, her symptoms interfere with her daily functioning, relationships, and work performance.
- Discomfort: Yes, she experiences significant distress, restlessness, and difficulty sleeping.
- Maladaptive Behavior: Yes, her excessive worry and anxiety are harmful and maladaptive.
- Norm or Value Violation: Yes, her behavior violates cultural norms and values of emotional regulation and coping.

Conclusion: Emily meets the criteria for a psychological disorder, specifically Generalized Anxiety Disorder (GAD).
6/5/24, 12:07 AM - Naqabi: - Case 4: Rachel, a 25-year-old artist, worries constantly about her creative abilities, finances, and relationships. She experiences restlessness, muscle tension, and difficulty sleeping, and has trouble focusing on her art.
 *Analysis:*

- Meets GAD criteria: Yes
- Deviance: Excessive worry deviates from societal norms
- Dysfunction: Interferes with daily life and relationships
- Discomfort: Experiences restlessness, muscle tension, and difficulty sleeping
- Maladaptive Behavior: Worry is maladaptive and interferes with functioning
- Norm or Value Violation: Violates cultural norms of emotional regulation.
6/5/24, 12:08 AM - Naqabi: - Case 5: David, a 35-year-old student, worries excessively about his academic performance, finances, and future career prospects. He experiences fatigue, irritability, and difficulty concentrating, and has trouble completing assignments.

 *Analysis:*

- Meets GAD criteria: Yes
- Deviance: Excessive worry deviates from societal norms
- Dysfunction: Interferes with daily life and relationships
- Discomfort: Experiences fatigue, irritability, and difficulty concentrating
- Maladaptive Behavior: Worry is maladaptive and interferes with functioning
- Norm or Value Violation: Violates cultural norms of emotional regulation

6/9/24, 10:11 PM - Muhammad Fawwad Ahmed: - Case 3: Emily, a 28-year-old marketing executive, experiences excessive worry about her job performance, finances, and relationships, and has difficulty sleeping, concentrating, and controlling her worry.

 Analysis: 

- Deviance: Yes, her excessive worry and anxiety deviate from societal norms.
- Dysfunction: Yes, her symptoms interfere with her daily functioning, relationships, and work performance.
- Discomfort: Yes, she experiences significant distress, restlessness, and difficulty sleeping.
- Maladaptive Behavior: Yes, her excessive worry and anxiety are harmful and maladaptive.
- Norm or Value Violation: Yes, her behavior violates cultural norms and values of emotional regulation and coping.

Conclusion: Emily meets the criteria for a psychological disorder, specifically Generalized Anxiety Disorder (GAD).

6/9/24, 11:27 PM - Naqabi: Here are the answers to the questions based on the case study:

1. What are the main symptoms Emily experiences due to her excessive worry?
Answer: Difficulty sleeping, concentrating, and controlling her worry.

2. How does Emily's anxiety affect her relationships?
Answer: The case study doesn't provide specific information, but excessive worry and anxiety can lead to strained relationships due to irritability, emotional distancing, or dependency.

3. What are the specific challenges Emily faces in her job performance due to her worry?
Answer: The case study doesn't provide specific information, but excessive worry and anxiety can lead to decreased productivity, missed deadlines, and poor decision-making.

4. How has Emily's sleep pattern been affected by her anxiety?
Answer: She has difficulty sleeping.

5. What strategies has Emily tried to control her worry, and were they effective?
Answer: The case study doesn't provide specific information, but often individuals with anxiety try avoidance, distraction, or self-soothing techniques, which may not be effective in managing their worry.

6. How does Emily's anxiety impact her daily functioning and routine?
Answer: Her symptoms interfere with her daily functioning, relationships, and work performance.

7. What are Emily's biggest fears and concerns regarding her finances?
Answer: The case study doesn't provide specific information, but individuals with financial anxiety often fear not meeting financial obligations, losing financial stability, or experiencing financial ruin.

8. How has Emily's anxiety affected her self-esteem and confidence?
Answer: The case study doesn't provide specific information, but excessive worry and anxiety can lead to decreased self-esteem and confidence due to feelings of inadequacy or helplessness.

9. What kind of support system does Emily have, and how have they tried to help her?
Answer: The case study doesn't provide specific information, but a support system can include friends, family, or mental health professionals who offer emotional support, encouragement, and coping strategies.

10. What treatment options or therapies would be suitable for Emily to manage her Generalized Anxiety Disorder (GAD)?
Answer: Cognitive-behavioral therapy (CBT), acceptance and commitment therapy (ACT), and relaxation techniques like deep breathing, progressive muscle relaxation, or mindfulness meditation can be effective in managing GAD.

10/6/24, 7:24 PM - Muhammad Fawwad Ahmed: Here are the answers and explanations for the questions on page 2 of the PDF.
ILP: Is There a Different Pattern in the Distribution of Accidental Deaths in a Certain Region Compared to the Pattern in the Entire United States?
1. State the null hypothesis:
●
H0: The distribution of accidental deaths in the particular region is the same as the distribution of accidental deaths in the entire United States.
Determine Alpha: Alpha is given as 5%.
2. Checking the Assumptions
●
(a) Find the expected counts and fill them in the table below.
●
To calculate the expected counts, multiply the total number of observed deaths (990) by the percentage of each cause of death in the entire United States. For example, the expected count for motor vehicle deaths is 990 * 0.45 = 445.5.
●
(b) Do all cells have expected counts greater than 5? Yes All cells have expected values greater than 5.
3. Compute the Test Statistic and Calculate the p-value
●
(a) Complete the calculation of the test statistic based on your table above by calculating the contribution of “other” accidental deaths to the total test statistic.
●
The contribution of "other" accidental deaths to the Chi-square statistic is calculated as:
●
((Observed - Expected)^2) / Expected = (150 - 178.3)^2 / 178.3 = 4.403
●
Adding this to the other values in the provided calculation:
●
X^2 = (442-445.5)^2/445.5 + (161-148.5)^2/148.5 + (42-39.6)^2/39.6 + (33-29.7)^2/29.7 + (162-158.4)^2/158.4 + 4.403 = 3.663
●
Calculate the p-value:
○
(i) The p-value is _____________ 0.598805.
○
(ii) The expected value of the test statistic assuming H0 is true is ____________ 5. This is the degrees of freedom, which is equal to the number of categories minus 1 (6 - 1 = 5).
○
(iii) The large p-value we obtained is consistent with the fact that our observed test statistic value is less than the expected test statistic value (under the null hypothesis).
4. Evaluate the p-value and Conclusion:
●
Evaluate the p-value:
○
What is your decision at a 5% significance level? Fail to Reject H0
●
Conclusion:
○
What is your conclusion in the context of the problem?
○
We fail to reject the null hypothesis that the distribution of accidental deaths in the particular region is the same as the distribution in the entire United States. There is not enough evidence to conclude that the pattern of accidental deaths in the region is different from the national pattern.
ILP: Comparison of the Distribution of Academic Degrees: Males Versus Females
1. State the null hypothesis:
●
H0: The distribution of academic degrees (Bachelor, Master, Professional, Doctorate) is the same for males and females.
Determine Alpha: Alpha is given as 1%.
2. Checking the Assumptions
●
(a) Show how the expected count 531.8 (first cell for males) was computed.
●
The expected count for a cell in a Chi-square test of homogeneity is calculated as:
●
(Row Total * Column Total) / Grand Total
●
In this case, the expected count for the first cell (males, Bachelor) is:
●
(1164 * 1171) / 2364 = 531.8
●
(b) Based on the table, do the assumptions appear to be met to perform the test? (Are all expected counts greater than 5?) Yes The problem does not provide the full table of expected counts, but it notes that all expected counts are greater than 5.
3. Compute the Test-Statistic and Calculate the p-value
●
Test-Statistic:
○
(a) Based on the output above, the test-statistic is ____ = ____________ X^2 = 9.5135.
●
Calculate the p-value
○
(b) Based on the output above, the p-value is _____________ 0.02319.
4. Evaluate the p-value and Conclusion:
●
Evaluate the p-value:
○
What is your decision at a 1% significance level? Fail to Reject H0
●
Conclusion:
○
What is your conclusion at a 1% significance level in the context of the problem?
○
We fail to reject the null hypothesis. There is not enough evidence to conclude that the distribution of academic degrees is different between males and females at the 1% significance level.
5. Would your decision and conclusion change if the significance level was:
●
5% instead of 1%? Yes. The p-value (0.02319) is less than 0.05, so we would reject the null hypothesis at a 5% significance level.
●
3% instead of 1%? Yes. The p-value (0.02319) is less than 0.03, so we would reject the null hypothesis at a 3% significance level.
●
2.3% instead of 1%? Yes. The p-value (0.02319) is less than 0.023, so we would reject the null hypothesis at a 2.3% significance level.
●
2% instead of 1%? No. The p-value (0.02319) is greater than 0.02, so we would fail to reject the null hypothesis at a 2% significance level.
Based on your answers, the p-value represents the minimum significance level at which the results would be statistically significant.
Cool-Down: Name That Scenario
Match each research question with the appropriate Chi-Square test that should be used to answer the question:
1. Is student status (in-state versus out-of-state) associated with one’s eventual graduation outcome (graduating versus not graduating)?
●
Answer: Chi-Square test of Independence. This question is asking about the relationship between two categorical variables (student status and graduation outcome) within a single population.
2. To test a theory that people have no preference among four different outdoor activities, you ask 100 people to select among jogging, bicycling, hiking, or swimming.
●
Answer: Chi-Square test of Goodness of Fit. This question is asking if the observed distribution of preferences for outdoor activities fits a theoretical distribution (no preference, meaning equal proportions for each activity).
3. A biostatistician would like to determine if the ratio of the blood type in storage for transfusions should be different in Hawaii from the mainland. She collected a sample of blood types of 10,000 people in Hawaii and that of 100,000 people in the mainland. She wishes to see if the breakdown of blood types (A, B, AB, and 0) is the same for both populations.
●
Answer: Chi-Square test of Homogeneity. This question is asking if the distribution of blood types is the same across two different populations (Hawaii and the mainland).

Question 1
○
Answer: Independence
○
Explanation: The researcher wants to determine if there is a relationship between scoring high or low on an artistic ability test and being right or left-handed. This involves examining two categorical variables: artistic ability (high/low) and handedness (right/left). The Chi-Square test of Independence is used to assess whether there is a relationship between two categorical variables.
●
Question 2
○
Answer: Homogeneity
○
Explanation: The national organization aims to compare the distribution of the highest education level completed (a categorical variable) between two groups: Republicans and Democrats. This situation aligns with the purpose of a Chi-Square test of Homogeneity, which is used to determine if two or more populations have the same distribution for a single categorical variable.
●
Question 3
○
Answer: Goodness of Fit
○
Explanation: The preservation society wants to compare the current distribution of fish types in the river after adding fish from hatcheries to the known percentages of fish types from ten years ago. They are essentially assessing if the new observed frequencies of fish types "fit" the expected frequencies based on the historical data. This directly aligns with the Chi-Square test for Goodness of Fit, which is used to determine if the observed data "fit" well compared to a specified distribution.
ILP: Is There a Different Pattern in the Distribution of Accidental Deaths in a Certain Region Compared to the Pattern in the Entire United States? (Page 3 of PDF)
●
Null Hypothesis: The distribution of accidental deaths in the particular region is the same as the distribution in the entire United States.
●
Alpha: 0.05
●
Expected Counts:
○
To find the expected counts for each cell in the table, multiply the total number of observed deaths (990) by the percentage from the national data for that cell. For example, the expected count for Motor Vehicle deaths would be 990 * 0.45 = 445.5. Doing this for each cell gives the following table:
●
Assumption Check: Yes, all cells have expected counts greater than 5.
●
Test Statistic Contribution of "Other":
○
The formula for calculating the contribution of each cell to the Chi-Square statistic is: ((Observed - Expected)^2) / Expected
○
For "Other" accidental deaths: ((150 - 168.3)^2) / 168.3 = 2.176 (approximately)
●
P-value: 0.598805
●
Expected Value of the Test Statistic: 5 (degrees of freedom)
●
Comparison to Expected Test Statistic Value: The observed test statistic (3.6635) is less than the expected test statistic value (5). The large p-value is consistent with this result.
●
Decision at a 5% Significance Level: Fail to Reject H0 because the p-value (0.598805) is greater than the significance level (0.05).
●
Conclusion: There is not enough evidence to conclude that the distribution of accidental deaths in the particular region is different from the national distribution.
ILP: Comparison of the Distribution of Academic Degrees: Males Versus Females (Page 3 of PDF)
●
Null Hypothesis: The distribution of academic degrees is the same for males and females.
●
Alpha: 0.01
●
Expected Count Calculation (First Cell for Males):
○
The expected count for a cell in a Chi-Square test of homogeneity is calculated as: ((Row Total * Column Total) / Grand Total)
○
For the first cell (males, Bachelor): ((1164 * 869) / 2000) = 531.8 (approximately)
●
Assumption Check: Yes, based on the output, we can assume that all expected counts are greater than 5 because the output does not state otherwise.
●
Test Statistic: 9.5135
●
P-value: 0.02319
●
Decision at a 1% Significance Level: Fail to Reject H0 because the p-value (0.02319) is greater than the significance level (0.01).
●
Conclusion at a 1% Significance Level: There is not enough evidence to conclude that there is a difference in the distribution of academic degrees between males and females.
●
Decision and Conclusion Changes at Different Significance Levels:
○
5% instead of 1%: Reject H0- There is a statistically significant difference.
○
3% instead of 1%: Reject H0- There is a statistically significant difference.
○
2.3% instead of 1%: Reject H0- There is a statistically significant difference.
○
2% instead of 1%: Fail to Reject H0- There is not a statistically significant difference.
●
Interpretation of the P-value: The p-value (0.02319) represents the minimum significance level at which we would reject the null hypothesis. That is, the results would be considered statistically significant at any significance level of 0.02319 or higher.

The Chi-Square test of Independence is used to assess if there is a relationship between two categorical variables.

10/6/24, 7:55 PM - Muhammad Fawwad Ahmed: The document you uploaded is focused on explaining and applying three different types of Chi-square tests: the Goodness of Fit Test, the Test of Independence, and the Test of Homogeneity. These tests are useful for analyzing categorical data, and the document includes problems, calculations, and questions that help you understand how to use these tests in practice. I will now explain each part of the document, answer the questions, and provide detailed explanations.

1. Chi-Square Goodness of Fit Test
The Goodness of Fit Test checks if the observed distribution of data fits a specified theoretical distribution. It answers the question: "Do the data fit well compared to a specified distribution?"

Example Problem:
You are given data about accidental deaths from different types of accidents (Motor Vehicle, Falls, Drowning, etc.) in a region, and you need to compare them with the national data. The goal is to determine if the pattern in the region is significantly different from the overall pattern in the United States.

Steps to Solve:
Null Hypothesis (H0): The null hypothesis states that the distribution of accidental deaths in the region matches the national distribution. In this case, H0 would be:

H0: The distribution of accidental deaths in the region is the same as the national distribution.
(This is from the "Task: Perform a Chi-square goodness of fit test" part of the PDF​(chi-square_tests_ ASSIG…).)
Expected Counts: To check if the regional data matches the national data, you first calculate the expected counts based on the national proportions. For instance, if 45% of accidental deaths in the U.S. are due to motor vehicle accidents, you would expect 45% of the regional deaths to be from motor vehicle accidents as well. The formula for expected counts is:

Expected count = Total regional deaths × Proportion from the national data.
This is used to fill in the expected counts in the table.
Checking Assumptions: For a Chi-square test to be valid, all expected counts must be greater than 5. In this case, you would calculate the expected counts for each type of accident and ensure that none of the expected counts is less than 5.
(This is described in "Checking the Assumptions" in the document​(chi-square_tests_ ASSIG…).)

Test Statistic Calculation: The Chi-square test statistic is calculated using the formula:
10/6/24, 7:55 PM - Muhammad Fawwad Ahmed: <Media omitted>
10/6/24, 7:55 PM - Muhammad Fawwad Ahmed: Where 
𝑂
𝑖
O 
i
​
  is the observed count and 
𝐸
𝑖
E 
i
​
  is the expected count for each type of accident. You calculate the difference between the observed and expected counts, square the difference, and divide by the expected count. Summing these values for all categories gives the Chi-square statistic.

p-value and Conclusion: Once the test statistic is calculated, you look up the p-value, which tells you whether the observed data significantly differ from the expected data. If the p-value is less than the significance level (0.05 in this case), you reject the null hypothesis, meaning that the regional distribution is significantly different from the national distribution.

If p-value > 0.05, fail to reject H0, meaning the distributions are not significantly different.
(This process is explained in the "Evaluate the p-value and Conclusion" section​(chi-square_tests_ ASSIG…).)
2. Test of Homogeneity
The Test of Homogeneity compares the distribution of a categorical variable across two or more populations. It answers the question: "Do two or more populations have the same distribution for a categorical variable?"

Example Problem:
You are given data on the number of academic degrees (Bachelor's, Master's, etc.) earned by males and females, and you need to test whether the distribution of academic degrees is the same for both genders.

Steps to Solve:
Null Hypothesis (H0): The null hypothesis for a test of homogeneity is that the distribution of degrees is the same for both males and females. So H0 would be:

H0: The distribution of academic degrees is the same for males and females.
(This is found under the "Hypothesis Test" section​(chi-square_tests_ ASSIG…).)
Expected Counts: To calculate the expected counts, you use the following formula:
10/6/24, 7:55 PM - Muhammad Fawwad Ahmed: <Media omitted>
10/6/24, 7:55 PM - Muhammad Fawwad Ahmed: For example, to calculate the expected count for males with a bachelor's degree, you would multiply the total number of males by the total number of bachelor's degrees and divide by the overall total number of degrees awarded.

Checking Assumptions: Again, for the Chi-square test to be valid, all expected counts should be greater than 5. In this problem, you calculate the expected counts for each combination of gender and degree type and ensure that all are greater than 5.
(This is explained in "Checking the Assumptions"​(chi-square_tests_ ASSIG…).)

Test Statistic Calculation: The test statistic is calculated using the same formula as in the goodness of fit test. After computing the test statistic, you compare it with the Chi-square distribution to find the p-value.

p-value and Conclusion: The p-value tells you whether the difference in the distribution of degrees between males and females is statistically significant. If the p-value is less than the significance level (0.01 in this case), you reject the null hypothesis, meaning that the distribution of degrees is different for males and females.
(This part is found in "Evaluate the p-value and Conclusion"​(chi-square_tests_ ASSIG…).)

Change in Conclusion at Different Significance Levels: The document also asks whether your conclusion would change if the significance level was different (for example, 5%, 3%, etc.). You can answer this by comparing the p-value to the new significance level. If the p-value is smaller than the new significance level, you reject the null hypothesis; otherwise, you fail to reject it.
(This is in the "Would your decision and conclusion change?" section​(chi-square_tests_ ASSIG…).)

3. Test of Independence
The Test of Independence checks whether two categorical variables are independent of each other. It answers the question: "Are two factors (or variables) independent for a population under study?"

Example Problem:
A researcher wants to know if artistic ability (high or low) is related to being right-handed or left-handed. The goal is to determine if there's a relationship between hand dominance and artistic ability.

Steps to Solve:
Null Hypothesis (H0): The null hypothesis is that the two variables (hand dominance and artistic ability) are independent. So H0 would be:

H0: Hand dominance and artistic ability are independent.
(This is inferred from the "Warm-Up: Check Your Understanding" section​(chi-square_tests_ ASSIG…).)
Expected Counts: As with the previous tests, you calculate expected counts using the formula for a contingency table:
10/6/24, 7:55 PM - Muhammad Fawwad Ahmed: <Media omitted>
10/6/24, 7:55 PM - Muhammad Fawwad Ahmed: You calculate the expected counts for each combination of hand dominance and artistic ability.

Test Statistic Calculation: The test statistic is again calculated using the Chi-square formula, comparing the observed counts with the expected counts for each category combination.

p-value and Conclusion: After calculating the test statistic, you find the p-value. If the p-value is less than the significance level (0.05 in this case), you reject the null hypothesis, meaning that there is a relationship between hand dominance and artistic ability.
(This can be found in the document under "Warm-Up"​(chi-square_tests_ ASSIG…).)

General Observations:
The Chi-square tests are used to compare observed data with expected data under a certain hypothesis. Whether you are testing for goodness of fit, homogeneity, or independence, the procedure is generally the same: state the null hypothesis, calculate expected counts, compute the test statistic, find the p-value, and draw a conclusion.

Each of these tests relies on categorical data, and the results are interpreted based on how well the observed data match the expected data under the null hypothesis. If the observed data deviate significantly from the expected data (based on the p-value), you reject the null hypothesis, indicating that the observed data are not consistent with the assumption made in the null hypothesis.

These tests are widely used in fields like biology, psychology, marketing, and social sciences, where researchers often need to understand patterns or relationships between categorical variables.

10/18/24, 9:14 PM - Naqabi: Clinical
Tibial Fracture
A break or crack in the tibia bone which can range from small stress fracture to severe complex fracture.

Causes:
1. Trauma ( Falls, Sport injuries, Car accidents)
2. Osteoporosis
3. Poor biomechanics

Symptoms:
1. Severe pain
2. Swelling
3. Deformity
4. Limited mobility
  
Treatment:
1. Pain management ( medication)
2. Physical therapy
3. Surgery

Condition: common peroneal nerve injury (from fibular head trauma)
Causes: Foot drop.
Symptoms: weak foot dorsiflexion & foot dragging.
Treatment:
1) Medications: pain relievers
2) Surgery: Nerve decompression in  sverve cases.

10/18/24, 10:49 PM - Muhammad Fawwad Ahmed: Common Peroneal Nerve Injury: Understanding the Condition

The peroneal nerve, located in the leg, controls movement and sensation in the foot and lower leg. Injury to this nerve can lead to various complications, including foot drop, a condition where the foot hangs limply. This presentation will delve into the anatomy, causes, symptoms, and treatment options for common peroneal nerve injuries.

10/19/24, 11:42 AM - Naqabi: Femoral Artery:

The major artery that supplies the lower limb, it passes through the thigh and continues as the popliteal artery in the knee region.

Deep femoral artery (profunda femoris): A branch of the femoral artery that supplies the muscles of the anterior, medial, and posterior compartments of the thigh.


2. Popliteal Artery:

Continuation of the femoral artery behind the knee (popliteal fossa).

It branches into:

Anterior tibial artery

Posterior tibial artery



3. Anterior Tibial Artery:

Passes to the anterior compartment of the leg.

Supplies muscles like the tibialis anterior, extensor digitorum longus, extensor hallucis longus, and fibularis tertius.

Continues as the dorsalis pedis artery to supply the foot.


4. Posterior Tibial Artery:

Supplies the posterior compartment of the leg.

Branches:

Fibular (peroneal) artery: Supplies the lateral compartment, which includes the fibularis longus and fibularis brevis muscles.

Medial and lateral plantar arteries: Supply the muscles of the sole of the foot.

Supplies muscles like the gastrocnemius, soleus, tibialis posterior, flexor digitorum longus, and flexor hallucis longus.

10/19/24, 9:15 PM - Naqabi: *Esophagus*
 _Introduction;_
1. The esophagus (gullet) is a muscular tube is connected to your stomach.
2. It is about 25cm  long and lies in the median plane in the thorax infront of the vertebral column behind the trachea.
3. The place where the esophagus joins the stomach is called the gastroesophagial junction.
10/19/24, 9:15 PM - Muhammad Fawwad Ahmed: i am feeling bad for you
10/19/24, 9:20 PM - Naqabi: _Structure of esophagus;_
1. Outer layer on Adventitia:
It attaches the esophagus to nearby parts of the body.
   2. Muscular layer:
Circular and longitudinal muscle fiber pushes food down into the stomach.
   3. Submucosa:
Contain glands that produce mucus, this keeps the esophagus moist.
   4. Mucosa:
It is the inner layer. It is moist to help the food pass smoothly into the stomach
10/19/24, 9:22 PM - Naqabi: _Functions of esophagus:_
1. The esophagus pass food and liquid from the mouth down the stomach.
2. This is accomplished by periodic contraction (peristalsis)
3. The cardiac sphincter relaxes to allow the food to pass into the stomach also it prevents reflex of gastric acid into the esophagus. <This message was edited>

10/19/24, 10:48 PM - Naqabi: Nerve Supply:-
•	Vagus nerve
•	cervical thoracic symphatic chains (T1-T4)
•	Mycenteric plexus
•	Submucosal plexus
Arteries Supply..
1)	Cervical esophagus
2)	Thoracic esophagus
3)	esophageal arteries
4)	Abdominal esophagus.
•	Left gastric artery (a branch of Celiac trunk)
•	Inferior phrenic artery (a branch of abdominal aorta)
Veins Supply:- 
1) Inferior thyroid veins
2) Azygos vein
3) Hemiazygos vein
4) left gastric vein 
5) esophageal Veins
10/19/24, 10:55 PM - Naqabi: Esophageal sphincter:-
The esophageal Sphincter refers to two main muscles that control the passage  between the esophagus and adjacent organs.
Upper Esophageal Sphincter: Located at the top of the esophagus, it prevents air from entering the esophagus during breathing & regulates food entry into the esophagus from throat.
Lower Esophageal Sphincter:- Located at the bottom of the stomach contents, including acid from refluxing back into the esophagus. <This message was edited>

Lymph vessels and Sympathetic fibers also pass the hilum

Kidney Coverings
- Fibrous Capsule :-  It Surrounds the Kidney. It closely adheres to Outer surface of kidney.

Perirenal fat:-
-Covers the fibrous Capsule.
Provides Cushioning to the kidneys.
Renal Fascia :-

-It encloses both kidneys and Suprarenal glands.
- It continues laterally by transvers alis fasc
Pararenal Fal:-
- It lies external to renal fascia. 
-Often present in large quality.
- It forms Puert of doneal lat. Retroperitoneal fat

10/20/24, 2:12 AM - Naqabi: 1- *Overview of Kidney Structure:-*

Each kidney has a dark brown outer cortex and a light brown inner medulla.

 *Medulla*
The medulla consists of renal pyramids with the apex (renal papilla) projecting medially.

*Medullary rays*

Medullary rays extend from the base of the renal pyramids into the cortex.

*Renal columns* 
Renal columns are extensions of the cortex between adjacent pyramids.

*Renal Sinus and Calyces :-*

*Renal sinus*

The renal sinus contains the upper end of the ureter, forming the renal pelvis.

*Renal pelvis*

The renal pelvis divides into 2–3 major calyces, each further dividing into 2–3 minor calyces.

*Apex*

The apex of the renal pyramid (renal papilla) indents each minor calyx.

*2-Important Relations of the Right Kidney:-*

*Anterior Relations:*

 Suprarenal gland, liver, duodenum, right colic flexure.

*Posterior Relations:*

 Diaphragm, pleural recess, 12th rib, psoas, quadratus lumborum, transversus abdominis muscles, subcostal, iliohypogastric, and ilioinguinal nerves.

*Important Relations of the Left Kidney:-*

*Anterior Relations:*

 Suprarenal gland, spleen, stomach, pancreas, left colic flexure, jejunum.

*Posterior Relations:*

 Diaphragm, pleural recess, 11th and 12th ribs, psoas, quadratus lumborum, transversus abdominis muscles, subcostal, iliohypogastric, and ilioinguinal nerves.

*3-Blood Supply of the Kidney :-*

*Renal artery*

Renal artery arises from the aorta at the level of the second lumbar vertebra.

Divides into five segmental arteries that enter the hilum, supplying different areas.

 *Lobar arteries*
Segmental arteries give rise to lobar arteries, which branch into interlobar arteries and then into arcuate arteries.

*Arcuate and interlobular arteries*

Arcuate arteries give rise to interlobular arteries that supply the cortex.

*Renal vein*
Renal vein drains into the inferior vena cava.

*4-Lymphatic and Nervous Supply:-*

*Lymph drainage:-*

Lymph drains to the lateral aortic lymph nodes around the origin of the renal artery.

*Nerve supply :-*

Nerve supply from the renal sympathetic plexus, with afferent fibers entering the spinal cord at T10, T11, and T12.

10/20/24, 3:13 AM - Naqabi: 1 - *Renal Pain* 

- *Causes*
- 
Stretching of the kidney capsule
Smooth muscle spasms in the renal pelvis
Inflammation or obstruction (e.g., kidney stones)

 *Symptoms*

Dull ache to severe flank pain
Pain radiating to the lower abdomen or groin
Associated symptoms (nausea, vomiting)

*Treatment*

Pain management strategies 

NSAIDs (Non-Steroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drugs)

Opioids for severe pain
Addressing underlying causes

Treatment for kidney stones
Managing infections

*Surgical Interventions*

Lithotripsy (shock wave therapy)
Ureteroscopy
Nephrolithotomy

2- *Kidney Transplantation*

 *Causes*

End-stage renal disease (ESRD)
Chronic conditions leading to kidney failure

Diabetes
Hypertension

 *Symptoms*

Severe fatigue
Fluid retention
Nausea and vomiting
Decreased urine output

 *Treatments*

Dialysis as a temporary solution

Kidney transplantation as a definitive treatment

10/20/24, 3:39 AM - Naqabi: *Ureter*

Two muscular tubes connect the kidneys to the posterior surface of the urinary bladder.

*Function of Ureter*

Urine is propelled by peristaltic contractions and filtration pressure from the glomeruli.

*Structure and Location*

Each ureter is approximately 10 inches (25 cm) long with three constrictions: where the renal pelvis joins the ureter, as it crosses the pelvic brim, and where it pierces the bladder wall.

The renal pelvis, located in the renal hilum, receives the major calyces.

The ureter runs behind the parietal peritoneum, adherent to the psoas muscle.

It crosses the bifurcation of the common iliac artery and runs down the lateral pelvis wall.

*Relations*

*Right Ureter:*

*Anteriorly:*

Related to the duodenum, terminal ileum, right colic and ileocolic vessels, testicular/ovarian vessels, and root of the mesentery.

*Posteriorly:*

Right psoas muscle and the bifurcation of the right common iliac artery.

*Left Ureter:*

*Anteriorly:* 

Sigmoid colon, sigmoid mesocolon, left colic vessels, testicular/ovarian vessels.

*Posteriorly:*

Left psoas muscle and bifurcation of the left common iliac artery.
Medially: Inferior mesenteric vein.

*Blood Supply*

Upper portion: Renal artery.

Middle portion: Testicular or ovarian artery.

Pelvis: Superior vesical artery.

Venous blood drains into corresponding veins.

*Lymph Drainage*

Lymph drains into the lateral aortic and iliac nodes.

*Nerve Supply*

Nerve supply from renal, testicular/ovarian, and hypogastric plexuses.
Afferent fibers travel with sympathetic nerves, entering the spinal cord at L1-L2 segments.

10/20/24, 4:26 AM - Naqabi: Introduction to Suprarenal Glands

*Location:* 

Yellowish, retroperitoneal organs that are found on the upper poles of the kidneys.

*Structure:*

It consist of two parts 

*Cortex:*  Yellow in color.

*Medulla:*  Dark brown in color.
Function: It produces vital hormones which help in different body functions.

*Cortex Of Suprarenal Gland*

*Hormones secreted:*

*Mineralocorticoids:* These regulate fluid and electrolyte balance.

*Glucocorticoids:* Regulate carbohydrate, protein, and fat metabolism.

*Sex Hormones:* Play a role in prepubertal sexual organ development.

*Medulla of Suprarenal Gland*

*Hormones Secreted :*

*Catecholamines*

*Epinephrine (adrenaline):* 

It takes part in an increase of heart rate and blood flow.

*Norepinephrine (noradrenaline):* 

Regulates blood pressure and stress response.

*Anatomical Location*

*Right Gland:* 

Pyramidal in shape, it caps the right kidney and is located behind the right lobe of the liver and inferior vena cava.

*Left Gland:* 

It is crescentic in shape, and the medial border of the left kidney goes along it. It lies behind the pancreas, lesser sac, and the stomach.

*Blood Supply and Venous Drainage*

*Arterial Supply:*

*Superior Suprarenal Artery:* Branch of the inferior phrenic artery.

*Middle Suprarenal Artery:*
 A branch issuing from the aorta.

*Inferior Suprarenal Artery:* Branch from the renal artery.

*Venous Drainage:* 

Single vein draining into the inferior vena cava on the right and renal vein on the left.

*Lymphatic Drainage and Nerve Supply*

*Lymphatic Drainage:* 

Ducts drain into the lateral aortic nodes.

*Nerve Supply:*

 Preganglionic sympathetic fibers from the splanchnic nerves supply the glands . 
Most of the nerves end in medulla of gland
10/20/24, 4:26 AM - Naqabi: <Media omitted>

10/20/24, 4:28 AM - Naqabi: *Diseases of Suprarenal Gland*

 *1-Cushing Syndrome*

Cushing syndrome happens when the body has too much of the hormone cortisol, often due to the adrenal glands becoming overactive.

*Cause:*

The main cause is adrenal gland overgrowth (hyperplasia). It can also be caused by tumors (adenoma or carcinoma) in the adrenal glands, especially in older people.

*Symptoms:*

Round, moon-shaped face
Extra fat around the belly (truncal obesity)
Unusual hair growth (hirsutism)
High blood pressure

*Treatment:*

Surgery to remove the adrenal tumors
Medicines like ketoconazole or metyrapone to lower cortisol levels

*2-Addison Disease*

Addison disease happens when the adrenal glands don't make enough of the hormones cortisol or aldosterone.

*Cause:*

It can be caused by tuberculosis or damage to both adrenal glands.

*Symptoms:*

Darkening of the skin, especially in skin folds
Weak muscles
Weight loss
Low blood pressure

*Treatment:*

Lifelong hormone therapy to replace missing hormones (e.g., hydrocortisone and fludrocortisone)
Emergency treatment for adrenal crises with IV corticosteroids and fluids

*3-Pheochromocytoma*

Pheochromocytoma is a tumor in the adrenal gland that causes it to make too much of the hormones epinephrine and norepinephrine.

*Cause*:

It happens because of a tumor in the adrenal medulla, which leads to an overproduction of these hormones.

*Symptoms:*

Sudden or ongoing high blood pressure
Headaches
Fast heartbeats (palpitations)
Excessive sweating

*Treatment:*

Surgery to remove the tumor
Before surgery, doctors control blood pressure with alpha-blockers and beta-blockers.

10/20/24, 12:21 PM - Muhammad Fawwad Ahmed: G
10/20/24, 12:21 PM - Muhammad Fawwad Ahmed: Anatomical Location

Right Gland: 

Pyramidal in shape, it caps the right kidney and is located behind the right lobe of the liver and inferior vena cava.

Left Gland: 

It is crescentic in shape, and the medial border of the left kidney goes along it. It lies behind the pancreas, lesser sac, and the stomach.

Blood Supply and Venous Drainage

Arterial Supply:

Superior Suprarenal Artery: Branch of the inferior phrenic artery.

Middle Suprarenal Artery:
 A branch issuing from the aorta.

Inferior Suprarenal Artery: Branch from the renal artery.

Venous Drainage: 

Single vein draining into the inferior vena cava on the right and renal vein on the left.

Lymphatic Drainage and Nerve Supply

Lymphatic Drainage: 

Ducts drain into the lateral aortic nodes.

Nerve Supply:

 Preganglionic sympathetic fibers from the splanchnic nerves supply the glands . 
Most of the nerves end in medulla of gland

In it lie the right and left hepatic ducts, the right and left branches of the hepatic artery, the portal vein, and sympathetic and parasympathetic nerve fibers (see Fig. 7.48). 10/20/24, 10:29 PM - Muhammad Fawwad Ahmed: The liver is completely surrounded by a fibrous cap- sule but only partially covered by peritoneum. The liver is made up of liver lobules. The central vein of each lobule is a tributary of the hepatic veins. In the spaces between the lobules are the portal canals, which con- tain branches of the hepatic artery, portal vein, and a tributary of a bile duct (portal triad). The arterial and venous blood passes between the liver cells by means of sinusoids and drains into the central vein.
10/20/24, 10:29 PM - Muhammad Fawwad Ahmed: Important Relations
• Anteriorly: Diaphragm, right and left costal margins, right and left pleura and lower margins of both lungs, xiphoid process, and anterior abdominal wall in the subcostal angle.
• Posteriorly: Diaphragm, right kidney, hepatic flexure of the colon, duodenum, gallbladder, inferior vena cava, and esophagus and fundus of the stomach.
10/20/24, 10:33 PM - Naqabi: •The porta hepatis, or hilum of the liver, is found on the posteroinferior surface and lies between the caudate and quadrate lobes. The upper part of the free edge of the lesser omentum is attached to its margins.
• In it lie the right and left hepatic ducts, the right and left branches of the hepatic artery, the portal vein, and sympathetic and parasympathetic nerve fibers and a few hepatic lymph nodes.

10/20/24, 10:52 PM - Naqabi: Topic Peritoneal Ligaments:
 *1. Falciform ligament;* The falciform ligament is a sickle-shaped fibrous connective tissue that attaches the liver to the anterior abdominal wall and diaphragm, supporting the liver's position and separating its left and right lobes.

 *2. Coronary Ligament;* Triangular fold  of peritoneum connecting bare area of liver to diaphragm.

 *3. Right triangular ligament;* Right extremity of coronary ligament is known as right triangular ligament.

 *4. Left triangular ligament;* Left extremity of coronary ligament is known as left triangular ligament.

 *5. Ligamentum Teres;* passes into a fissure on the visceral surface of the liver and joins the left branch of the portal vein in the portal hepatis.

 *6. Ligamentum Venosum;* attached to the left branch of the portal vein and ascends in a fissure on the visceral surface of the liver to attach above to the inferior vena cava.

 *7. Lesser Omentum;* arises from the edges of the porta hepatis and the fissure for the Ligamentum venosum and passes down to the lesser curvature of the stomach.
10/20/24, 10:52 PM - Naqabi: null
10/20/24, 11:06 PM - Naqabi: *Bare Area*
Area where liver is directly in contact with the diaphragm and do not cover with peritoneum.

 *Blood Supply*
 _•Hepatic Artery_ (branch of Celiac Artery) divides into right and left terminal branches that enter the porta hepatis.
 _•Portal Vein_ divides into the right and left terminal branches that enter the porta hepatis behind the arteries. The hepatic veins (three or more) emerge from the posterior surface of liver and drain into the inferior vena cava.

10/20/24, 11:59 PM - Muhammad Fawwad Ahmed: Lymph Drainage
The liver produces a large amount of lymph-about one third to one half of all body lymph. The lymph vessels leave the liver and enter several lymph nodes in the porta hepatis. The efferent vessels pass to the celiac nodes. A few vessels pass from the bare area of the liver through the diaphragm to the posterior mediastinal lymph nodes.
Nerve Supply
Sympathetic and parasympathetic nerves form the celiac plexus. The anterior vagal trunk gives rise to a large hepatic branch, which passes directly to the liver

10/21/24, 12:08 AM - Naqabi: Clinicals Of Liver:

1. Jaundice (Yellowing of skin and eyes): Indicates liver dysfunction, bile duct obstruction, or hepatitis.

2. Palmar Erythema (Redness of palms): Suggests liver cirrhosis, hepatitis, or liver failure.

These signs can indicate underlying liver disease or dysfunction.

10/21/24, 12:20 AM - Muhammad Fawwad Ahmed: Hepatic Ducts
The right and left hepatic ducts emerge from the right and left lobes of the liver in the porta hepatis  After a short course, the hepatic ducts unite to form the common hepatic duct .
The common hepatic duct is about 1.5 in. (4 cm) long and descends within the free margin of the lesser omentum. It is joined on the right side by the cystic duct from the gallbladder to form the bile duct.

10/21/24, 12:38 AM - Naqabi: •The bile duct (common bile duct)is about 3 inches long.
The bile duct ends below by piercing the medial wall of the second part of the duodenum about half way down its length. Occasionally , the bile and pancreatic ducts open separately into the duodenum.
•Bile is a fluid that is made and released by the liver and stored in the gallbladder. Bile helps with digestion. It breaks down fats into fatty acids, which can be taken into the body by the digestive tract.
